<!-- THE APP OWNS THE WHOLE SCREEN — which is also what the iOS shell does, and
     that parity is the point of this file's shape (#204).

     This layout used to be a vertical LinearLayout splitting the Activity by
     WEIGHT: widget_root 3, a green-on-black [BOOT] console ScrollView 2. A flat
     40% of the screen, in every orientation, reserved for debug narration —
     including in every app generated from the template, since this file is a
     byte-identical mirror (TemplateDriftTests).

     Measured on hardware (1220×2712 @ density 480) before it was removed:

                       usable      widget_root        [BOOT] strip
         portrait      759.3dp     455.3dp (60%)      304.0dp (40%), showing 84dp of text
         landscape     317.3dp     190.3dp (60%)      127.0dp (40%)

     In landscape the demo page needs 283.3dp and got 190.3dp, so its second
     button was cut in half at exactly the strip's top edge and its third button
     never appeared. And the overflow was not even CLIPPED: every
     BnYogaFrameLayout sets `clipChildren = false` to match iOS's
     `clipsToBounds == NO`, so the content was drawn and then PAINTED OVER by the
     opaque strip, which the LinearLayout drew after it. A page that just stops,
     with nothing on screen to explain it.

     Yoga was never implicated — worth recording, because it is the natural first
     guess. Both shells re-solve the whole tree against the new bounds on any host
     resize (YogaLayout's addOnLayoutChangeListener → calculateAndApply, and iOS's
     twin in HostViewController.viewDidLayoutSubviews). The space was gone before
     Yoga ever saw it.

     The narration was NOT lost with the strip: it goes to logcat through
     BnShellLog, gated at Info since #200/#202, and `scripts/devloop.ps1` reads it
     from there rather than from the screen. iOS never had an on-screen panel at
     all, so removing this one CLOSES a shell divergence.

     RECLAIMING SPACE IS NOT THE GENERAL FIX, and this comment should not be read
     as claiming otherwise: a page whose content exceeds the viewport should
     SCROLL, which is what BnScroll is for and what works at any screen size.
     Making the host bigger only postpones the truncation. -->

<!-- Phase 6.1: the host root is a BnYogaFrameLayout, NOT a stock FrameLayout.
     A stock one is not inert: every addView/setText in a batch calls
     requestLayout(), and the ensuing traversal re-measures this container and
     re-places every TOP-LEVEL node at (0, 0, hostW, hostH) — behind Yoga's
     back, in the real Activity only (never in a detached-root test), and the
     resize listener's bounds guard sees no change so nothing repairs it. Yoga
     owns ALL placement, including the top level. See BnYogaFrameLayout's KDoc. -->
<io.blazornative.shell.BnYogaFrameLayout
    xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
    android:id="@+id/widget_root"
    android:layout_width="match_parent"
    android:layout_height="match_parent"
    android:background="#FFFFFF" />
